But the Romans had other meanings of Privilegium, which was what they called Jus Singulare as opposed to Jus Commune. “Thus we have Privilegia of soldiers in making testaments (Dig. 28. 6. 15), the Privilegia of several classes of persons as excuses from ‘tutela,’ and very frequently Privilegia in favour of creditors ‘in con- cursu,’ especially the Fiscus, persons under age, &c.⁷’ (Savigny, System, i. 62).
